s in merging multiple LLM-generated summaries coherently while preserving speaker context. Mocks would merge without error. You need to execute the real sequence: split audio → call speech-to-text on each segment (real API) → call LLM to summarize each (real LLM) → call LLM again to merge (real LLM) → verify coherence. Context loss, speaker attribution misalignment, and information loss across segments only appear with real LLM calls.","test_description":"Test with real audio >60 minutes (or synthetic test recording simulating this). Verify segmentation logic splits at boundaries without losing audio. For each segment, call the real speech-to-text API and verify speaker labels are preserved. For each resulting transcript, call the real LLM to generate a segment summary. Then call the real LLM with all segment summaries to produce a final merged summary. Verify the final summary is coherent (no contradictions), speaker attributions are maintained across segments, and no information is lost in the merge.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires multiple sequential LLM calls (summarize + merge) to catch real failures in coherence and context preservation across segments.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.75}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — upload audio, transcribe, summarize, deliver structured output — completes without manual intervention for a real meeting recording.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is the end-to-end agent pipeline. Real failures include upload timeouts, API rate-limiting, format incompatibility between steps, speech-to-text failure, LLM timeout, and integration breakdowns. Mocks hide all of these. You need the complete workflow with real APIs, real file handling, real network calls, and real LLM execution to expose failures in coordination, resilience, and error handling.","test_description":"End-to-end test with a real >30 minute me